WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.920
Thank you, everybody. I'm very happy to be here. My name is Mike Garcia, and I'm a Director

00:00:10.920 --> 00:00:14.520
of Data Services for Medible, and today I want to talk about how you can scale your

00:00:14.520 --> 00:00:20.680
data validation workflow with the pointblank R package and Posit Connect. Ten years ago,

00:00:20.680 --> 00:00:25.160
I was a data analyst for a very large utility company in the country, and one of my main

00:00:25.160 --> 00:00:31.120
responsibilities was to create and maintain these energy savings forecasts, and I have

00:00:31.120 --> 00:00:35.080
a confession to make. I really didn't know what I was doing, and I was never confident

00:00:35.080 --> 00:00:40.080
in the numbers that I was producing, and that was because there was no formal process for

00:00:40.080 --> 00:00:44.880
these forecasting tasks. And when it came time to do our data validation, to check our

00:00:44.880 --> 00:00:49.439
work, it involved a group of us going into a conference room, throwing everything up

00:00:49.439 --> 00:00:54.520
on a big screen, and just opening up Excel workbooks, tracing through cells, and looking

00:00:54.520 --> 00:01:00.639
at where the formulas landed. It was not a fun process. Today, I can confidently say

00:01:00.639 --> 00:01:06.320
that this is not how my team operates at Medible. In fact, we have robust procedures for everything

00:01:06.320 --> 00:01:10.599
that we do, especially when it comes to data validation. And that's what I want to talk

00:01:10.599 --> 00:01:17.040
about today. By building upon our foundation of data quality measures at Medible, expanding

00:01:17.040 --> 00:01:23.239
the functionality of the pointblank R package, and leveraging Posit Connect with its API,

00:01:23.239 --> 00:01:27.839
we were able to design and implement a fully end-to-end scalable solution for our data

00:01:27.839 --> 00:01:33.160
validation needs. And so, for the next 15 minutes, I want to highlight four challenges

00:01:33.160 --> 00:01:40.239
that we came across, and how we addressed them. Before we dive any deeper, I'd like

00:01:40.239 --> 00:01:45.040
to give a little bit of background about Medible. So, Medible is a technology startup with a

00:01:45.040 --> 00:01:49.559
state-of-the-art platform for conducting clinical trials. Our clients are some of the largest

00:01:49.559 --> 00:01:55.800
pharma companies and contract research organizations in the world. And we license our platform

00:01:55.800 --> 00:02:00.760
to these clients in the form of web and mobile apps that we build and deploy for them as

00:02:00.760 --> 00:02:06.360
a service. These apps are used by patients and caregivers and doctors all throughout

00:02:06.360 --> 00:02:11.160
their trial participation. And some of the activities that they may do on these apps

00:02:11.160 --> 00:02:17.279
are completing pain assessments on a weekly basis, or entering diary data every day detailing

00:02:17.279 --> 00:02:22.559
their experiences with a new investigational drug. All of these activities with the apps

00:02:22.559 --> 00:02:27.440
generate a lot of data, and that data gets stored securely on the Medible platform. And

00:02:27.440 --> 00:02:32.839
it's the job of my team in data services at Medible to transfer that data from the platform

00:02:32.839 --> 00:02:37.600
to the hands of the client. But that's not as straightforward as you would think, because

00:02:37.600 --> 00:02:44.039
data models between studies and projects vary. And that's primarily driven by three factors.

00:02:44.039 --> 00:02:49.039
One, protocols just vary in complexity and design, and so our apps sometimes need to

00:02:49.039 --> 00:02:54.639
as well in order to accommodate the needs. Second, trials can last for years, but our

00:02:54.639 --> 00:03:00.600
technology moves a lot faster than that. So if we want to implement bug fixes or introduce

00:03:00.600 --> 00:03:06.839
a new capability, sometimes we need to do that on a study-by-study basis. And lastly,

00:03:06.839 --> 00:03:10.399
clients have very strict expectations on what they want their data to look like and how

00:03:10.399 --> 00:03:14.119
they want to receive that. And that's also driven by the fact that they have these large

00:03:14.119 --> 00:03:18.759
systems in their organization. And so it's up to us to work with them to make sure that

00:03:18.759 --> 00:03:24.679
they can ingest the data that we are sending to them. Now, all this flexibility meant that

00:03:24.679 --> 00:03:29.440
our processes, especially for data validation, had to be flexible, but that meant manual.

00:03:29.440 --> 00:03:34.160
And four years ago, that was okay. That worked well. But as the number of studies that we

00:03:34.160 --> 00:03:39.240
supported grew exponentially, we started to notice some data quality issues creeping into

00:03:39.240 --> 00:03:44.360
our deliverables. So late last year, we made this conscious effort to really streamline

00:03:44.360 --> 00:03:48.839
and automate a lot of what we were doing related to data validation, and that's when we stumbled

00:03:48.839 --> 00:03:56.320
upon the Pointblank package. Pointblank allows you to validate your data using these simple

00:03:56.320 --> 00:04:02.119
yet powerful validation functions. For example, if you wanted to test if a set of values in

00:04:02.119 --> 00:04:06.039
a column were less than or equal to another value or set of values in another column,

00:04:06.039 --> 00:04:11.000
there's a function for that. The way that it works is you create what is known as an

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:16.480
agent object. You pass to it a single target table that you want to validate and some other

00:04:16.480 --> 00:04:22.799
data, like how you want to be alerted if a test case would fail. You then pass this object

00:04:22.799 --> 00:04:27.720
to these validation functions, and these act as sort of instructions for what your agent

00:04:27.720 --> 00:04:32.640
should do when it's ready to validate. And then when you are ready to validate, you call

00:04:32.640 --> 00:04:36.760
the interrogate function. So in essence, you're interrogating the agent for the information

00:04:36.760 --> 00:04:42.679
that you want. And the result is a really nice-looking, easy-to-digest HTML report.

00:04:42.679 --> 00:04:47.040
On the left, you have a nice color-coding scheme that tells you what passed, what failed,

00:04:47.040 --> 00:04:51.839
or if you hit another threshold that you set when creating your agent. Each record represents

00:04:51.839 --> 00:04:58.160
a validation function that you set and the columns next to it that you apply them to.

00:04:58.160 --> 00:05:02.320
And on the right, you have some descriptive statistics telling you how many cases were

00:05:02.320 --> 00:05:08.399
run for each function, how many passes and fails, and their proportions. And at first

00:05:08.399 --> 00:05:12.040
glance, it was perfect. It was everything that we needed. The way that it integrated

00:05:12.040 --> 00:05:17.040
with packages that we used already and technologies, and also its intuitive API and its source

00:05:17.040 --> 00:05:22.799
code was easy to digest. However, once we actually started to implement it for our processes

00:05:22.799 --> 00:05:27.239
and data, we noticed there were four specific challenges that we had to address before we

00:05:27.239 --> 00:05:30.880
could do that. And that's what I'm going to walk through right now.

00:05:30.880 --> 00:05:34.920
So, the first challenge is we wanted Point Blank to operate on more than just a single

00:05:34.920 --> 00:05:41.239
target table. Here's an example of a data model for our study, for a very simple study

00:05:41.239 --> 00:05:45.959
that we may see. And if we wanted to test each individual table, we would need to create

00:05:45.959 --> 00:05:50.799
each individual agents and apply them to the tables. And that's at the core of Point Blank.

00:05:50.799 --> 00:05:55.040
And we didn't want to change that for our needs. Instead, we wanted to bundle all of

00:05:55.040 --> 00:06:00.119
these agents together into a collection that we can then operate on that collection. And

00:06:00.119 --> 00:06:06.359
so, in typical R fashion, we wrapped everything into a list, and we applied some processing

00:06:06.359 --> 00:06:11.279
to it that's specific to our needs, and we called it a test plan. And so, essentially,

00:06:11.279 --> 00:06:14.640
it's a list of agents with some extra goodies that I'll talk about in a little bit. If you're

00:06:14.640 --> 00:06:19.559
familiar with Point Blank, this is very much like a multi-agent report, and we borrowed

00:06:19.559 --> 00:06:24.480
a lot from that. We're just extending upon it to perform operations on that actual multi-agent

00:06:24.480 --> 00:06:29.040
instead of it being just a reporting function. So, in the background, this is a very simple

00:06:29.040 --> 00:06:34.799
concept, but we modified lots of Point Blank and PINs functions to actually do what we

00:06:34.799 --> 00:06:39.959
wanted to do with this. And also, we integrated it with the DM package, which we use for our

00:06:39.959 --> 00:06:45.799
data modeling needs. So, when we want to create a test plan, it's very straightforward. You

00:06:45.799 --> 00:06:51.279
pass in your individual agents, and then you pass to it also a test name, which we will

00:06:51.279 --> 00:06:55.179
reference later on. And some of the data that gets stored with the test plan are the name

00:06:55.179 --> 00:06:59.220
that we just passed through, as well as a test version that we get from PINs and Connect,

00:06:59.220 --> 00:07:05.500
and I'll share very briefly. Now, when we're ready to validate our collection of agents

00:07:05.500 --> 00:07:11.820
or our test plan, we have to run interrogate on each individual function, so each individual

00:07:11.820 --> 00:07:18.779
agent. So, we basically map the interrogate function to all the agents, and we also force

00:07:18.779 --> 00:07:23.220
the user to specifically pass in the data that they're going to validate, which is a

00:07:23.220 --> 00:07:28.579
little different than how Point Blank works natively in my experience, but it also prevents

00:07:28.579 --> 00:07:36.500
any scoping rules that we may encounter later while we're doing some sharing. And the result

00:07:36.500 --> 00:07:41.260
is what's known as a multi-agent report. So, again, we borrowed this. We streamlined the

00:07:41.260 --> 00:07:46.739
formatting of it a little bit for our needs, and we also did some things like streamline

00:07:46.739 --> 00:07:51.140
the title of it. So, now the title, we have our test name, and we have the test version

00:07:51.140 --> 00:07:57.339
for traceability reasons. The second challenge is we wanted to implement sharing and reusability

00:07:57.339 --> 00:08:02.859
of the test plans that our team is creating. So, I showed a simple data model before, but

00:08:02.859 --> 00:08:06.980
in reality, they look more like this, and you can guess that if we're validating each

00:08:06.980 --> 00:08:13.820
table, the code, the Point Blank code to generate all that can get pretty large and pretty unwieldy

00:08:13.820 --> 00:08:21.059
quickly. So, one feedback that we heard from the team is, how can we reuse these test plans

00:08:21.059 --> 00:08:25.619
so that we're not recreating the wheel every single time we start a new study or want

00:08:25.619 --> 00:08:31.899
to iterate on an existing test plan? So, copying-pasting is an option, but it's not really a practical

00:08:31.899 --> 00:08:37.900
one in a production setting. So, if we revisit our create test plan function again, we could

00:08:37.900 --> 00:08:41.780
do a little more in it. We could add some functionality. So, we're going to take each

00:08:41.780 --> 00:08:46.900
of the individual agents inside of this test plan, and we're going to actually extract

00:08:46.900 --> 00:08:51.700
the code that's needed to create that individual agent. So, it's kind of like we're reverse

00:08:51.700 --> 00:08:56.380
engineering that part. And the reason for that is that we want to actually store that

00:08:56.380 --> 00:09:01.700
code instead of the actual object, the agent object itself on Connect. So, we're going

00:09:01.700 --> 00:09:06.940
to take that code, and we're going to convert it to JSON, and we're going to write it to

00:09:06.940 --> 00:09:12.340
Connect as a pin. And JSON is because we want full transparency for anyone who's not a data

00:09:12.340 --> 00:09:16.260
scientist to be able to go on to Connect and look to see what's actually going on with

00:09:16.260 --> 00:09:20.859
the code. Now, with PositConnect, if you have a lot of content on there, sometimes

00:09:20.859 --> 00:09:25.460
it's a little hard to filter around. So, you can set tags for easy filtering and navigating.

00:09:25.460 --> 00:09:32.539
So, we set tags so that this could be a test plan. And by default, when you publish content

00:09:32.539 --> 00:09:37.419
to Connect, it's just shared with yourself. You have to go into the UI and change that.

00:09:37.419 --> 00:09:42.140
So, we actually use the PositConnect API to do that in the function itself. So, then we

00:09:42.140 --> 00:09:48.179
share access with our data team by default. Here's a screenshot of what that pin looks

00:09:48.179 --> 00:09:54.580
like on Connect. So, in typical fashion, you have the time it was last updated, the format,

00:09:54.580 --> 00:10:00.059
which is JSON, and a streamlined description for it. And then you have your raw metadata

00:10:00.059 --> 00:10:06.380
that's provided by pins. And with pins, you're also able to pass in some user-defined metadata.

00:10:06.380 --> 00:10:10.460
And so, we hook up to that, and we include the name of the person that last modified

00:10:10.460 --> 00:10:15.099
the test plan, as well as a commit message for that new version of the plan. So, we want

00:10:15.099 --> 00:10:21.539
this to act more like a Git-based system. And if we expand upon that object, you're

00:10:21.539 --> 00:10:26.419
not supposed to read this, but what I want to show here, it's actual JSON. It's unformatted,

00:10:26.419 --> 00:10:30.820
but it's still JSON. And on the right in the box, you're just seeing that we're sharing

00:10:30.820 --> 00:10:36.340
it with our internal data team group. So, if we want to take this and actually bring

00:10:36.340 --> 00:10:41.820
it back into our studio and iterate on it, or use it as a jumping off point for the next

00:10:41.820 --> 00:10:46.380
project, we have a convenience function called View Test Plan, where all we do is supply

00:10:46.380 --> 00:10:51.979
the test name, and if not the latest version, the test version. And what it does is in your

00:10:51.979 --> 00:10:56.739
IDE, opens up a new file pane, dumps all the code in there, and it's ready for you to modify

00:10:56.739 --> 00:11:01.940
as needed. The third challenge was we wanted to automate with Posit Connect, because we

00:11:01.940 --> 00:11:08.340
use it already for our study deployments. So, when you want to automate something with

00:11:08.340 --> 00:11:15.419
R, R Markdown is usually the answer, or Quarto, or Flex Dashboard. And when you do that, there's

00:11:15.419 --> 00:11:20.739
also a lot of ways you can create that document. So, we wanted to streamline that part. And

00:11:20.739 --> 00:11:25.380
so, we created a function called Create Validate that actually takes your data and your test

00:11:25.380 --> 00:11:29.979
plan from Connect, and it feeds it into a template that we've created internally, so

00:11:29.979 --> 00:11:33.380
that it kind of streamlines that. So, all you have to do is run this function, provide

00:11:33.380 --> 00:11:37.539
your data and your test name, and you get an R Markdown document that's ready to be

00:11:37.539 --> 00:11:45.099
knit. Then, as we want to automate it, we have to deploy it to Connect. We can use the

00:11:45.099 --> 00:11:49.739
great push button deployment option, but even still, when you do that, there are some options

00:11:49.739 --> 00:11:53.859
that you need to set that we take for granted. Like, do you want to link your code? Do you

00:11:53.859 --> 00:11:59.580
want to force an update if something exists already? Do you have all the dependencies

00:11:59.580 --> 00:12:03.380
ready, those little check boxes that show up? So, again, we wanted to just make it easy

00:12:03.380 --> 00:12:08.020
as possible to do this in a production setting. So, we created Deploy Validation, which essentially

00:12:08.020 --> 00:12:13.780
wraps the deploy doc function from RS Connect. And similar to creating a test plan, we tag

00:12:13.780 --> 00:12:22.820
it, we share it with our data team, and we set a default schedule using the API to run.

00:12:22.820 --> 00:12:28.140
And what that looks like is a Flex Dashboard with two tabs. The first tab is Data and Sources.

00:12:28.140 --> 00:12:31.900
It includes all the data that's needed to run and execute this test plan. So, that includes

00:12:31.900 --> 00:12:36.500
the target table, references, as well as any reference documentation that's needed. If

00:12:36.500 --> 00:12:40.580
you're familiar with Point Blank, we use that for, say, preconditions. And then on the bottom,

00:12:40.580 --> 00:12:46.580
we have a URL to the Connect page for that pin, for that test plan that's being used

00:12:46.580 --> 00:12:51.419
in here, again, for traceability reasons. On the right, I'm just showing that it is

00:12:51.419 --> 00:12:58.140
scheduled by default for output once a week. And here is that multi-agent report that I

00:12:58.140 --> 00:13:03.940
showed earlier, again, being shared with the data team. Now, of course, we want to know

00:13:03.940 --> 00:13:09.299
what's happening when we execute these tests. And with Point Blank, we show that it integrates

00:13:09.299 --> 00:13:15.299
with Blastula. So, we wanted to, again, borrow that concept and apply it to a test plan.

00:13:15.299 --> 00:13:18.940
So, we're going to revisit our execute test plan function again. And all we're going to

00:13:18.940 --> 00:13:24.580
look for is if any of the individual agents in that test plan failed. If they failed,

00:13:24.580 --> 00:13:29.020
I want you to send me an email saying that it did with a specific template. Even if it

00:13:29.020 --> 00:13:36.059
didn't fail, I still want an email telling me that it ran and it was successful. Here's

00:13:36.059 --> 00:13:42.059
an example of what that email looks like. So, your subject will have the number of cases

00:13:42.059 --> 00:13:48.780
that failed. This is an example of an email with a failed test plan that failed the time

00:13:48.780 --> 00:13:53.340
the test was run and a textualized version of that multi-agent report. So, originally,

00:13:53.340 --> 00:13:57.940
we had the multi-agent report coming through email. The formatting was a little wonky,

00:13:57.940 --> 00:14:02.419
and we realized it wasn't that actionable for the team. So, this is what we have coming

00:14:02.419 --> 00:14:08.099
to our inboxes. And lastly, we wanted to enable monitoring of everything that's going on.

00:14:08.099 --> 00:14:11.979
So, you can imagine we have all of these test plans being executed automatically in our

00:14:11.979 --> 00:14:19.380
production setting. And we also want to monitor the health of our dashboards. I'm sorry, we

00:14:19.380 --> 00:14:23.619
want to monitor the health of all of our studies and test plans that are being executed. The

00:14:23.619 --> 00:14:28.340
point of this is we want to drive change upstream to the engineers, to the study teams that

00:14:28.340 --> 00:14:34.099
are actually creating these apps. So, in order to monitor it, we need to save our validation

00:14:34.099 --> 00:14:39.659
results first. And so, again, let's revisit execute test plan. And we have this pseudocode

00:14:39.659 --> 00:14:44.460
here, save validation results, where when that runs, it takes your executed test plans

00:14:44.460 --> 00:14:50.979
and it passes them through as a pin into our cloud storage buckets. And then from there,

00:14:50.979 --> 00:14:57.479
we're actually extracting summary data from these test plans that go into a small database.

00:14:57.479 --> 00:15:02.179
And that database is powering a shiny app that we've created that helps us monitor what's

00:15:02.179 --> 00:15:06.940
going on with the health of all these programs. So, we have some value boxes up top telling

00:15:06.940 --> 00:15:11.659
us how many tests run, what's our failure rate. This is all fake data, by the way. What's

00:15:11.659 --> 00:15:15.659
our failure rates and what are kind of the most offensive tests, the ones that are failing

00:15:15.659 --> 00:15:20.940
the most. We have a table of everything that was run and also some historical trends of

00:15:20.940 --> 00:15:28.619
failure rate to see what's going, what's improving or what's not. And so, in summary, by addressing

00:15:28.619 --> 00:15:35.859
these four challenges, we were able to create that end-to-end scalable solution. But really,

00:15:35.859 --> 00:15:39.460
it wouldn't have been possible with all the work that came before us. And so, from a medical

00:15:39.460 --> 00:15:43.419
perspective, it was all those data quality measures that we actually used as the basis,

00:15:43.419 --> 00:15:48.219
as the foundation for these test plans in knowing what to validate. And in terms of

00:15:48.219 --> 00:15:56.900
our packages and technologies, everything here that's on the screen made this all possible.

00:15:56.900 --> 00:15:58.900
And that's it. Thank you.

00:15:58.900 --> 00:16:13.900
Thank you, Michael. So, what was like the biggest challenge that you all had in being

00:16:13.900 --> 00:16:18.900
able to set up all this infrastructure?

00:16:18.900 --> 00:16:25.539
We had the infrastructure with just the fact that we automated data transfers. It was one

00:16:25.539 --> 00:16:29.739
getting to the mindset of actually making code to run these tests instead of doing it

00:16:29.739 --> 00:16:34.580
manually, which the whole team had done. But then also, our data is pretty specific in

00:16:34.580 --> 00:16:38.179
terms of like how the data is stored and what the column name looked like, things like that.

00:16:38.179 --> 00:16:40.979
Things that you kind of took for granted. And originally, we tried to run point blank

00:16:40.979 --> 00:16:45.739
on it. We would get errors. And so, it's just basically going into the source code and just

00:16:45.739 --> 00:16:49.960
kind of picking apart what we needed, what we needed to change. And that's what took

00:16:49.960 --> 00:16:52.380
most of the time. That was the biggest challenge.

00:16:52.380 --> 00:16:53.380
Thank you again.

00:16:53.380 --> 00:16:54.380
Thank you.

00:16:54.380 --> 00:16:54.380


00:16:55.539 --> 00:16:56.539
Thank you.

